\title{Dual-Threshold Consistency and Backdoor Scrubbing for Robust Diffusion Models}

\author{GPT-4o \& Claude\\
Department of Computer Science\\
University of LLMs\\
}

\newcommand{\fix}{\marginpar{FIX}}
\newcommand{\new}{\marginpar{NEW}}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Diffusion models have shown significant promise in generative tasks, but their effectiveness relies heavily on the quality of training data. When trained on corrupted or noisy data, these models become vulnerable both to compromised reconstruction fidelity and to malicious backdoor attacks. In this work, we propose Dual-Threshold Consistency and Backdoor Scrubbing (DTCBS), a novel training framework designed to address two major shortcomings of conventional methods. DTCBS overcomes the reliance on noisy training data by leveraging a two-stage consistency training scheme based on a double application of Tweedie’s formula, and defends against poisoning attacks by introducing a reverse-noise screening process that identifies samples exhibiting inconsistent denoising behavior across adjacent noise scales. By flagging samples via a consistency gate and either down-weighting or removing them during training, our comprehensive experiments on CIFAR-10 demonstrate that DTCBS not only achieves competitive denoising performance compared to a base method but also substantially improves the robustness of the model by reducing the presence of backdoor triggers. Quantitative evaluations using metrics such as mean squared error, PSNR, SSIM, detection rates for poisoned samples, and false positive rates on clean data validate the proposed approach as a mathematically principled and systematically refined training protocol that simultaneously strengthens reconstruction fidelity and enhances adversarial resilience.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
Diffusion models have emerged as a leading paradigm in generative modeling, particularly for high-resolution image synthesis. These models rely on the gradual introduction of noise followed by a reverse process that recovers the original data. Training on corrupted data, however, raises critical challenges. Noise may obscure the true data signal, reducing denoising accuracy, while even subtle adversarial or backdoor manipulations can compromise model performance by introducing hidden triggers that lead to memorization and potential copyright issues. Recent works such as Ambient Diffusion and SURE-based methods have attempted to address noisy data, though they often rely on approximations that sacrifice reconstruction quality and lack robust defense against malicious data injections.

In response, our proposed DTCBS framework enhances diffusion model training in two key ways:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Dual-Threshold Training}: Uses a consistency gate based on cosine similarity across adjacent noise scales and a reverse-noise screening process based on reconstruction error.
  \item \textbf{Iterative Refinement}: Alternates updates between the denoiser and screening mechanisms to progressively clean the training set.
\end{itemize}

Our contributions are threefold:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Enhanced Sampling}: We develop a two-stage consistency training method leveraging a double application of Tweedie’s formula, extending sampling capability to lower noise levels.
  \item \textbf{Robust Defense}: We introduce a reverse-noise screening component to detect anomalous behavior induced by malicious triggers, reducing memorization effects.
  \item \textbf{Progressive Refinement}: We design an iterative refinement protocol where the denoiser and screening mechanisms are updated in tandem for stable convergence under adversarial conditions.
\end{itemize}

\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}
Recent literature has focused on training diffusion models on corrupted and noisy datasets. Methods such as Ambient Diffusion and SURE-based approaches extend traditional diffusion processes to noisy training scenarios, but often at the cost of reconstruction fidelity. Concurrently, backdoor defense strategies for discriminative models—such as targeted noise injection and adversarial training—have been explored; however, these methods do not directly translate to the generative context due to variability in noise patterns and trigger placements. Unlike previous works that solely aim to reconstruct uncorrupted data, our method integrates a dual screening process that not only recovers the underlying signal but also actively filters out malicious inputs by employing both a consistency criterion (via cosine similarity) and a reverse-noise screening step (via mean squared error). This dynamic adjustment of thresholds based on model performance offers enhanced robustness compared to static, single-criterion approaches.

\section{Background}
\label{sec:background}
Diffusion models reconstruct clean data by learning to invert a noise corruption process, typically within the framework of denoising score matching. The forward process corrupts data via progressive noise injection, while the reverse process estimates the gradient of the data distribution. Central to this approach is Tweedie’s formula, which connects the noisy observation to the underlying clean signal by means of a conditional expectation. Traditional implementations rely on a single application of Tweedie’s formula, but our method employs a double application to achieve reliable denoising even at noise levels below those present in the training data.

Moreover, recent studies on backdoor attacks have revealed that generative models are particularly susceptible to subtle, localized perturbations that persist through the diffusion process. These perturbations can lead to issues such as sample memorization and unauthorized reproduction. Our work addresses this risk by introducing a reverse-noise screening procedure, where small, controlled Gaussian noise perturbations are applied to each sample. By evaluating the reconstruction error using mean squared error and quantifying consistency with cosine similarity across noise scales, our approach integrates dual-threshold measures within a unified training pipeline to ensure both high reconstruction fidelity and robust defense against backdoor triggers.

\section{Method}
\label{sec:method}
\subsection{Dual-Threshold Training}
Our method begins with a two-stage consistency training process. The denoiser, based on a double application of Tweedie’s formula, produces outputs at multiple noise levels. For each noise scale, the denoiser's output is compared with that at an adjacent noise scale using cosine similarity. If the similarity drops below a predefined threshold (e.g., 0.95), the sample is flagged by the consistency gate.

\subsection{Reverse-Noise Screening}
In parallel, a reverse-noise screening process is applied. A small Gaussian noise (with a standard deviation of 0.02) is added to the input samples, and the denoiser processes these perturbed inputs. The reconstruction error, measured by the mean squared error, is computed for each sample. Samples that show errors exceeding a preset threshold (e.g., 0.01) are marked as potentially malicious.

\subsection{Iterative Refinement}
The final component of DTCBS is an iterative refinement protocol where the denoiser and screening modules update alternately. Initially, the model is trained on the full dataset. The screening mechanisms then identify and flag problematic samples. In subsequent training iterations, flagged samples are either removed or assigned lower weights, enabling the model to progressively improve both reconstruction fidelity and the reliability of the screening process.

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\begin{algorithmic}
  \State Initialize model parameters and complete training dataset
  \For{each training epoch}
    \State Process the entire dataset through the denoiser
    \For{each sample}
      \State Evaluate cosine similarity between denoised outputs at adjacent noise scales
      \If{cosine similarity < threshold}
        \State Flag the sample via the consistency gate
      \EndIf
      \State Perturb sample with small Gaussian noise
      \State Compute reconstruction error (mean squared error)
      \If{error > threshold}
        \State Flag the sample as potentially malicious
      \EndIf
    \EndFor
    \State Update model parameters using the filtered dataset
  \EndFor
\end{algorithmic}
\caption{Iterative Refinement Procedure in DTCBS}
\end{algorithm}

\section{Experimental Setup}
\label{sec:experimental}
To evaluate DTCBS, we conducted experiments on the CIFAR-10 dataset with synthetically perturbed data. The standard CIFAR-10 training set was augmented with controlled backdoor triggers on approximately 10% of the images. These triggers, implemented as small localized perturbations (e.g., a brightened square in a corner), simulate malicious modifications.

In Experiment 1, each sample is subjected to the reverse-noise screening routine, where a small Gaussian noise (standard deviation of 0.02) is added, and the reconstruction error is computed. Key metrics recorded include the detection rate (percentage of poisoned samples flagged) and the false positive rate (percentage of clean samples incorrectly flagged).

Experiment 2 focuses on the consistency gate. A synthetic subset of CIFAR-10 images is perturbed with multiple noise levels (0.01, 0.02, and 0.03 standard deviation), and cosine similarity between consecutive denoised outputs is computed. Samples with an average similarity below 0.95 are flagged.

Experiment 3 implements the full iterative refinement protocol, where two parallel training pipelines are compared: one using a base method and the other employing DTCBS. Both use a simple convolutional denoiser architecture, the Adam optimizer, and a fixed learning rate of 1e-3. Training is performed over multiple epochs (preliminary tests run for 3 epochs, with full experiments extending to 30 epochs). Evaluation metrics include mean squared error, peak signal-to-noise ratio (PSNR), structural similarity index (SSIM), as well as detection rates for poisoned samples and the evolution of flagged samples over epochs. Implementation is done in PyTorch, with logging and visualization supported by standard libraries such as NumPy, matplotlib, and seaborn.

\section{Results}
\label{sec:results}
The experimental evaluation demonstrates clear advantages of DTCBS over the base method. In Experiment 1, the reverse-noise screening mechanism flagged a significantly higher percentage of malicious samples, leading to an improved detection rate while maintaining an acceptable false positive rate on clean data. The distribution of reconstruction errors showed that samples with injected triggers exhibited distinctly higher mean squared errors.

