\caption{Evolution of flagged sample counts during iterative refinement.}
\end{figure}

Together, these results substantiate that the dual-threshold screening approach in DTCBS preserves high reconstruction fidelity in noisy environments while robustly defending against backdoor triggers.

\section{Conclusions and Future Work}
\label{sec:conclusion}
We introduced Dual-Threshold Consistency and Backdoor Scrubbing (DTCBS), a novel framework for robustly training diffusion models on noisy and potentially malicious datasets. By integrating a two-stage consistency training regime with a reverse-noise screening process and iteratively refining both the denoiser and screening mechanisms, DTCBS effectively enhances reconstruction quality while defending against backdoor triggers. Experimental results on CIFAR-10, supported by detailed quantitative evaluations and visualization of loss curves and detection metrics, demonstrate that DTCBS significantly improves the detection rate of malicious samples without severely impacting clean data. This approach provides a principled balance between leveraging noisy data to reduce issues such as memorization while actively filtering out adversarial modifications. Future work may explore optimizing threshold parameters, reducing training overhead, and extending the framework to larger, more diverse datasets.

